=========================================
std::auto_ptr (C++98)
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

What is std::auto_ptr?

- Introduced in C++98
- First smart pointer
- Automatic memory management (RAII)

-----------------------------------------

Problem

auto_ptr transfers ownership on copy.

Example

auto_ptr<int> p1(new int(10));

auto_ptr<int> p2 = p1;

After copy

p1 ----> nullptr
p2 ----> 10

Copying unexpectedly modifies the source object.

-----------------------------------------

Demo

#include <iostream>
#include <memory>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    auto_ptr<int> p1(new int(23));

    auto_ptr<int> p2 = p1;

    if(!p1)
        cout << "p1 is nullptr\n";

    cout << *p2;
}

Output

p1 is nullptr
23

-----------------------------------------

Problems

• Ownership transferred on copy
• Source pointer becomes nullptr
• Violates normal copy semantics
• Not suitable for STL containers

-----------------------------------------

Why not STL containers?

STL containers internally copy/move elements.

Since auto_ptr transfers ownership on copy,
elements may unexpectedly become nullptr,
leading to unpredictable behavior.

-----------------------------------------

Why Deprecated?

• Confusing copy semantics
• Breaks STL container requirements
• Explicit ownership transfer is better

-----------------------------------------

Replacement

auto_ptr   ❌

unique_ptr ✔ (Exclusive ownership)

shared_ptr ✔ (Shared ownership)

-----------------------------------------

Interview Answer

std::auto_ptr was deprecated because copying it transferred ownership, 
leaving the source pointer null. This violated normal copy semantics and made it 
unsafe for STL containers. C++11 replaced it with std::unique_ptr, 
which deletes copy operations and requires explicit ownership transfer using std::move().
